04412nam a2200745Ia 9783110772364DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20232023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2023930087  a97831107723647 a10.1515/97831107723642doi  a(DE-B1597)612446  a(OCoLC)1378138813  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aHV553b.T86 2023 4aHV553b.T87 2023 7aSOC0400002bisacsh04a363.3482231 aTurner, Bryan S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Theory of Catastrophe /cBryan S. Turner. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (V, 153 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDe Gruyter Contemporary Social Sciences ,x2747-5689 ;v1900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tChapter 1 Introduction: Disasters, Crises, and Catastrophes -- tChapter 2 Risk Society and Liquid Modernity -- tChapter 3 Enlightenment and Catastrophe -- tChapter 4 Plagues, Famines and Population -- tChapter 5 Colonial Catastrophes and Genocide -- tChapter 6 War: The Cascade of Catastrophes -- tChapter 7 The Economics of Catastrophe -- tChapter 8 Catastrophe and Utopian Hope -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tErratum to: Chapter 7: The Economics of Catastrophe0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSociology has developed theories of social change in the fields of evolution, conflict and modernization, viewing modern society as essentially unstable and conflict driven. However, it has not seriously studied catastrophe. A Theory of Catastrophe develops a sociology of catastrophes, comparing natural, social and political causes and consequences, and the social theories that might offer explanations. A catastrophe is a general and systematic breakdown of social and political institutions resulting, among other things, in what we could call a catastrophe consciousness. The Greek ‘cata-strophe’ formed the conclusion to a dramatic sequence of strophes. The cata-strophe was the final act of a drama, namely its denouement. Catastrophic denouements are without hope: genocides, military occupations, plagues, famines and earthquakes. A Theory of Catastrophe analyzes Pompeii, the Black Death, colonial genocide in North America, WWI and the Spanish Flu, and Nazi Germany and finally this century: terrorism, new wars, climate change and pandemics. As a study of sociological theory, Bryan Turner discusses Spengler’s Decline of the West, Marxism as a theory of catastrophic capitalism, messianic movements, Weber on modernity, and risk society. He concludes by comparing optimism and pessimism, and the idea of inter-generational justice.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aDisaster relief. 0aDisastersxSocial aspects. 0aDisasters. 4aKatastrophe. 4aKatastrophensoziologie. 4aSozialer Wandel. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Disasters & Disaster Relief.2bisacsh  aCatastrophe.  aDisaster.  aSocial Change.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1z97831111757820 cEPUBz97831107724490 cprintz978311077223440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311077236440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110772364423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110772364/original  a978-3-11-117578-2  DG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1b2023  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles